        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Typically, yes. By limiting exposure to a subset of buyers rather than the full open market, off-market sales reduce competition. Less competition usually means lower price. The exception is when the property has a very specific buyer profile and the agent has high-quality buyers waiting — in which case the right buyer can still be found without broad public marketing."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why would a seller choose to sell off-market in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Sellers choose off-market for privacy (not wanting neighbours or colleagues to know they're selling), to test the market without public days-on-market accumulating, to avoid the disruption of open homes while the property is occupied by tenants or family, or because a genuine buyer has already been identified through the agent's network."
      }
    },
